1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:18,445
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa

2
00:00:18,593 --> 00:00:32,619
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,557 --> 00:00:37,762
So the next refuge that we take is the Dharma.

4
00:00:38,203 --> 00:00:44,252
Dharma itself is a word that has a root meaning in that which sustains or upholds.

5
00:00:45,954 --> 00:00:52,064
And it's often translated as, especially in the Far East, as the law, the true law.

6
00:00:53,365 --> 00:00:59,534
But it's also regularly translated as the teachings or the dispensation of the Buddha.

7
00:01:00,088 --> 00:01:06,097
And the first thing that we say about it is that it's sva-kāṭo, which means it's well expounded.

8
00:01:07,420 --> 00:01:24,325
So, when he begins his teaching, and he's teaching for 45 years, you can see from the early level of the scriptures that it's very spontaneous, in the sense that he knows what he's talking about, but it's not been fully formalized.

9
00:01:25,402 --> 00:01:38,361
and it takes a few years, I don't know how long, for it to become formalized in terms of, you know, the Four Noble Truths, Eightfold Path, Five Spiritual Faculties, and then he goes on and on, you see.

10
00:01:39,302 --> 00:01:46,772
And, of course, the purpose for that was that it was a way of remembering things, the mnemonics, you see.

11
00:01:47,513 --> 00:01:50,477
You know, in those days, they didn't have memory sticks, you know, they just had their heads.

12
00:01:51,379 --> 00:01:54,784
So, they had to remember things just by these lists,

13
00:01:55,625 --> 00:02:14,021
and then very slowly towards the end of the scriptures by the time you know he's many after many years you can see the beginning of the just lists you know just lists and it's the they say that's the beginning of this later work called the Abhidhamma and

14
00:02:15,266 --> 00:02:30,375
Because what you get from the scriptures are specific answers to certain questions given by individuals, it gives a feeling of a sort of immediacy about his teaching.

15
00:02:30,735 --> 00:02:36,887
You know, he's not a philosopher writing in his room and publishing a book.

16
00:02:37,340 --> 00:02:40,703
It's like he's out on the streets and somebody comes and asks him a question.

17
00:02:41,343 --> 00:02:42,944
And then he gives that answer, you see.

18
00:02:43,225 --> 00:02:48,730
So, no particular scripture gives you the fullness of his teachings.

19
00:02:48,931 --> 00:02:51,092
You have to sort of try and get it all together.

20
00:02:51,813 --> 00:02:55,056
That's why you get these books on what the Buddha taught.

21
00:02:56,598 --> 00:02:57,900
Because it's difficult.

22
00:02:57,919 --> 00:03:03,685
You have to read quite a few scriptures to sort of congregate all his teachings.

23
00:03:04,205 --> 00:03:10,711
But eventually you can actually reduce them to the 37 factors leading to awakening.

24
00:03:11,873 --> 00:03:29,554
There's a scholar, Warder, who studied the two main bodies of scriptures that still remain, ours and the other ones called the other sect, the other school, the Sarvastavardhan school, which is actually only in the Chinese.

25
00:03:30,133 --> 00:03:32,456
And when he studied them both, he came up with this

26
00:03:32,757 --> 00:03:38,504
The only thing you could say that the Buddha actually taught were these 37 factors that lead to enlightenment.

27
00:03:38,525 --> 00:03:46,716
And the ones that you know, like the Four Noble Truths, the Eightfold Path, the Seven Factors of Enlightenment, the Five Spiritual Faculties, and it just goes on.

28
00:03:46,895 --> 00:03:51,061
And you get 37, and that's really the bedrock of his teaching, you see.

29
00:03:53,745 --> 00:03:56,508
And it's all fully explained.

30
00:03:56,609 --> 00:03:59,693
I mean, there are commentaries on it, of course, as usual.

31
00:04:00,145 --> 00:04:07,818
But eventually that's what comes through is the fullness of the teaching, both as theory and as practice.

32
00:04:08,580 --> 00:04:12,568
So that's why we say it's svākāto, it's well expounded.

33
00:04:15,193 --> 00:04:16,997
The next thing is saṇḍitiko.

34
00:04:18,439 --> 00:04:19,841
This means it's

35
00:04:20,293 --> 00:04:24,100
immediate, and that's the thing about the dharma.

36
00:04:24,141 --> 00:04:32,617
Although it suggests a future to us in terms of development and end-game and ibana and all that, the effects are immediate.

37
00:04:33,459 --> 00:04:35,403
You don't have to wait tomorrow to see effects.

38
00:04:35,423 --> 00:04:37,987
As soon as you meditate, the effect is there.

39
00:04:38,028 --> 00:04:41,694
It's not something that you do now for some future result.

40
00:04:43,041 --> 00:04:45,925
And that's the immediacy of the dharma, you see.

41
00:04:46,706 --> 00:05:03,649
So questions about future lives and all that sort of stuff, they sometimes lead you off the actual point of the practice, which is that the enlightenment has to be here, the awakening has to be here,

42
00:05:03,629 --> 00:05:15,723
or it's not here, it's immediate, and if we're not in a state of wisdom at this present moment, then there's no point in doing the practice.

43
00:05:16,363 --> 00:05:23,432
If you're trying to achieve something, if you're doing something now to achieve something in the future, then you're missing out on the present moment.

44
00:05:23,452 --> 00:05:30,261
It's like when you travel somewhere and your head's exactly where you're going to arrive, so you miss the whole train journey.

45
00:05:32,906 --> 00:05:43,166
So it's this bringing ourselves back into the present moment and actually seeing that the Dhamma is right here and now, it's to be seen right here and now, felt here and now, experienced here and now.

46
00:05:44,269 --> 00:05:50,139
And that's the quality of the Dhamma, that it's immediate.

47
00:05:53,360 --> 00:05:56,766
The next quality is akāliko, which means timeless.

48
00:05:57,449 --> 00:06:01,656
It's not something which belongs to the process of time.

49
00:06:01,716 --> 00:06:03,420
It stands outside time.

50
00:06:03,901 --> 00:06:05,906
It's a sort of underlying law.

51
00:06:07,269 --> 00:06:11,637
Just like you might get these basic laws of our universe.

52
00:06:11,887 --> 00:06:37,947
they're not to do with time as such, they're to do with something which as it were transcends time, it's right there within, you might say it subsists the process of time so the Dharma is already there, the Buddha didn't remember invent it, he discovered it, he said it was an ancient path he basically rediscovered or discovered what was already there

53
00:06:38,651 --> 00:07:00,922
And what is already there is not, in this sense, the spiritual laws, such as the whole teaching around desire, which is a cause of suffering, is something that is just there as a substrate to the whole process of what we see around us, the creation of the world.

54
00:07:02,043 --> 00:07:05,048
So in that sense it's archaic, it's timeless, you see.

55
00:07:07,372 --> 00:07:09,595
The other, the next one is Ehi Pasigo.

56
00:07:09,896 --> 00:07:14,420
So, this means, you know, to be experienced.

57
00:07:14,600 --> 00:07:16,382
It's actually got to be experienced.

58
00:07:16,442 --> 00:07:18,064
It's not something you just keep in your head.

59
00:07:18,684 --> 00:07:27,934
When the first monks and nuns asked to join him in the ascetic life, he simply said, Ehi, come.

60
00:07:27,954 --> 00:07:29,755
Ehi Pasigo, come and try.

61
00:07:30,857 --> 00:07:34,139
That was the initial ordination.

62
00:07:34,271 --> 00:07:34,892
Come and try.

63
00:07:35,814 --> 00:07:36,636
I want to join you.

64
00:07:36,656 --> 00:07:38,278
Come and have a go.

65
00:07:38,298 --> 00:07:46,413
So this ehipassiko refers to the actual practice that it has to be experienced.

66
00:07:46,434 --> 00:07:47,295
It has to be done.

67
00:07:48,396 --> 00:07:55,470
And it's in doing it that one actually sees this immediacy, this business of immediacy.

68
00:07:57,273 --> 00:07:59,459
And that's something else, there's something else involved in that.

69
00:07:59,480 --> 00:08:01,105
In fact, it's not a belief system.

70
00:08:01,346 --> 00:08:03,250
It's no good believing what the Buddha says.

71
00:08:03,271 --> 00:08:04,355
It's not going to get you anywhere.

72
00:08:04,755 --> 00:08:07,384
It's something that has to be tested.

73
00:08:10,283 --> 00:08:20,636
The next one is opanaiko, it means that it's leading somewhere, so it's not as though we're doing the practice which is not going somewhere.

74
00:08:20,976 --> 00:08:35,294
Now I've just said that we don't practice for the future, but in a sense there is a future, there is this eventuality of complete awakening, the complete end of suffering, I mean that's what's being offered.

75
00:08:35,274 --> 00:08:59,881
but the practice is in the immediate moment but it is leading somewhere and it's leading somewhere in two levels it's leading somewhere psychologically it's purifying the heart so eventually we should feel better eventually and it's leading somewhere spiritually in the sense that it is going to an end point which we call Nibbāna

76
00:09:00,166 --> 00:09:05,442
and Nibbāna can be described as a transcendent experience.

77
00:09:05,864 --> 00:09:12,504
That's what he called himself, he referred to himself as the Tathāgata, the transcendent one, the one who's gone beyond.

78
00:09:13,918 --> 00:09:43,807
so that's this opanaiko and the final one is pachatang veditabo vinyuhiti and that simply means that it's to be it's open to those who are wise who are open to it so it's something that a person is drawn to at a particular level of seeking within themselves whatever their quest is then they will seek it out and at some point they'll come across this ancient path

79
00:09:44,259 --> 00:09:52,635
And remember that the ancient path, although it's well expounded by the Buddha, is not peculiar to him.

80
00:09:52,975 --> 00:09:56,844
I mean, it's there within most religions that you find.

81
00:09:58,486 --> 00:10:03,956
Whether it's taught well enough, who knows, but the point is that it's there within us.

82
00:10:04,932 --> 00:10:11,221
We ourselves, having made a decision, can become self-enlightened if you want to become a bodhisattva.

83
00:10:12,322 --> 00:10:16,107
That's a person who makes the decision to become fully self-enlightened.

84
00:10:16,408 --> 00:10:21,775
So it's not as though the path exists somewhere outside us, it's right there within us.

85
00:10:22,937 --> 00:10:31,529
And if we're wise enough, if we're driven by a desire to be liberated from our...

86
00:10:32,809 --> 00:10:52,775
from our suffering then we'll naturally seek the end of suffering that's one of the statements of the Buddha it's suffering itself which makes us want to seek the end of suffering and whether we like it or not we will achieve it you see it's just one of the it's part of the evolution you might say of consciousness

87
00:10:54,712 --> 00:10:55,975
That's getting a bit metaphysical.

88
00:10:56,696 --> 00:11:04,985
So this is, so that's what we're taking refuge in when we say, you know, when we're actually saying I take refuge in the Dharma.

89
00:11:05,746 --> 00:11:12,916
And this word refuge, see, you go there to feel safe, don't you?

90
00:11:13,297 --> 00:11:14,938
You're taking refuge in something.

91
00:11:16,240 --> 00:11:19,565
Finding it as a medicine, something that's going to help you.

92
00:11:20,986 --> 00:11:24,230
So that's the, that's taking refuge in the Dharma.

93
00:11:25,476 --> 00:11:29,129
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

94
00:11:29,149 --> 00:11:40,751
May you be fully liberated sooner rather than later.

